"{\"correct\": \"no\", \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function returns an array of sinc values, but the sinc function is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) which can result in float values. When you use the astype function to convert the result to int64, it truncates the decimal part which can lead to incorrect results.\", \"patch\": \"5c5\\n< sinc_result = np.sinc(original_data).astype(original_data.dtype)\\n---\\n> sinc_result = np.sinc(original_data)\\n7,8c7,8\\n< assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n< assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n> assert np.isclose(sinc_result[0], 1), \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n> assert np.isclose(sinc_result[1], 0.9092974268256817), \\\"Results not equal to sinc(1)\\\"\"}"